snippet.textDisplay: If a backdoor exists, then your data is not secure. Period. Even if we somehow had the guarantee that all of the government folks with access would be good actors, the backdoor itself is a gaping vulnerability, and one or more bad actors are going to get access to it. Either privacy and security win out, and governments don't have access, or governments get access, and privacy and security go down the drain. Encryption experts have been saying for some time now that backdoors are fundamentally incompatible with security, but governments just don't want to listen.
snippet.textOriginal: If a backdoor exists, then your data is not secure. Period. Even if we somehow had the guarantee that all of the government folks with access would be good actors, the backdoor itself is a gaping vulnerability, and one or more bad actors are going to get access to it. Either privacy and security win out, and governments don't have access, or governments get access, and privacy and security go down the drain. Encryption experts have been saying for some time now that backdoors are fundamentally incompatible with security, but governments just don't want to listen.
